|  DUSD High School Graduation and UC/CSU  Requirements |
| :---: |

Students will earn a DUSD high school diploma upon completing the required course of study. Students must complete at least 230 credits over a four-year period.  High school courses completed in middle school will be included on the DUSD transcript and can be used to fulfill specific course requirements for high school graduation, but they are not counted toward the total number of credits required for graduation and will not be calculated in the GPA. Community service is encouraged but is not currently a requirement for graduation. Additional Details can be found in [DUSD Board Policy 6146.1](https://simbli.eboardsolutions.com/Policy/ViewPolicy.aspx?S=36030635&revid=F6plusNk38L3qs54nAhDsUcvA==&ptid=amIgTZiB9plushNjl6WXhfiOQ==&secid=ruE8yj8gaZHBkLjNHWmKZw==&PG=6&IRP=0&isPndg=false)

In addition to the comprehensive high school setting, DUSD provides two other educational options for students to earn a high school diploma: 

**Valley High School** (VHS) is a continuation high school serving 10th, 11th and 12th grade students who are significantly credit deficient and unlikely to graduate if they remain at a comprehensive high school. Course offerings at VHS reflect the credit recovery needs of the students as well as courses that students will take for the first time. Students who remediate courses earn 5 credits a quarter and courses taken for the first time earn students 2.5 credits a quarter, mirroring the credit earning structure of the comprehensive high schools. Due to the small VHS learning community, elective offerings can be limited and students have the option to take classes at the comprehensive high schools, through the ROP program, or local community colleges. Students are required to complete the Graduate Portfolio; details available on the website. Students enrolled at Valley High School must meet all state graduation requirements and earn a total of 180 credits.

**York Alternative Learning Center** (YALC) offers high school courses through the online curriculum of Edgenuity.  Courses available are UC A-G approved and meet the DUSD comprehensive high school graduation requirements. Students are required to take the online assessments in person with a credentialed teacher at least once a week. Students enrolled at York Alternative Learning Center must meet all state graduation requirements and earn a total of 230 credits.  

It is possible for students to take classes in more than one setting during the same year. Students should speak with their counselor if interested in exploring this option.

|  College and University Admission Requirements |
| ----- |

**California Community College Requirement**  
California residents are eligible to apply for admission to a community college if they are high school graduates or if they are over 18 years of age. 

**California State University and the University of California Admission Requirements**  
Whether you have a goal of a 4-year college or you are still deciding what to do after high school strive to meet the UC/CSU A \- G requirements:

* Earn C’s or higher (remediate when semester grade is lower than a C)  
* Finish 11 of the requirements by the end of 11th Grade  
* Meet “recommended” requirements when possible

**Private and Out-of-State Colleges and Universities**  
Admission requirements for private and out-of-state colleges vary by institution. Please contact the college directly or contact a DUSD school counselor for additional information.

**NCAA Eligibility**   
For a list of NCAA-approved courses, please visit the [NCAA Eligibility Center](https://www.ncaa.org/sports/2021/2/8/student-athletes-future.aspx) and speak with the student’s counselor.

# 

Each grade level includes courses required for graduation. In addition, students must complete a number of additional elective courses of their choosing to earn the 230 credits required for a DUSD comprehensive high school diploma. **When registering, you should indicate several alternate elective choices as conflicts may make first choices difficult to schedule. The elective courses listed will be included in individual school’s schedules only if there is sufficient enrollment. Due to scheduling conflicts, course changes after the deadline may not be possible. Therefore, students should make selections wisely. If a student selects an elective and receives it in their schedule, the student will be expected to adhere to this schedule.**

You will be planning a course of study for the **full** school year, both Fall and Spring semesters.  **Please consult your school’s material for the change request deadline. Course request changes may not be made after the deadline**. Students will meet individually with their counselor to go over course requests before March 15\. 

**Guidelines for Enrolling in Advanced, Honors and AP Classes:**

Students should be aware that courses designated as advanced, honors, and advanced placement (AP) exceed the level of rigor for that subject required by the California State Standards. In some cases, the course descriptions list the essential skills students are expected to have mastered prior to starting the course. These essential skills are included to advise the student what prior knowledge or competencies are needed to help them be successful in this course. If a student has any questions about whether they are prepared for an advanced, honors, or AP course, they should speak with a teacher in that subject area or with their counselor. 

Students are encouraged to enroll in an honors or AP level course at some point during their high school career. These courses are an excellent way to sample the rigor of college-level courses with the support provided in a high school environment. Because these courses are more rigorous, most require additional study time and practice for students to be successful. Consequently, students and their families should consider commitments outside of school as well as student mental health and wellness when determining whether, when, and how many advanced, honors, or AP courses to take.

Annual Limit on AP/Honors Courses: Beginning the 2026-2027 school year, per Resolution NO. 2025/26-37, a student may enroll in **no more than four (4) Advanced Placement/Honors courses in any single academic year**. 

Four-year Limit on AP/Honors Courses: Beginning with the class of 2029 a student may enroll in no more than **eleven (11) total Advanced Placement/Honors** courses during their high school career (grades 9-12). *The policy is not retroactive. Courses already completed remain unchanged.* 

For more information on the resolution and for access to the appeal request, see [Establishing Limits on Advanced Placement and Honors Courses: A Family & Student Guide](https://bit.ly/3YN62rE). You can also visit the [AP section](https://bit.ly/3NOJoN9) of the District website. 

**Courses Taken Outside of DUSD:**

DUSD does not allow credit by exam for any DUSD courses. In order to earn credit toward graduation and have courses placed on their high school transcript, students must have taken the course after completing 8th grade.

* Refer to DUSD [Board Policy 6146.11 and Administrative Regulation 6146.11](https://simbli.eboardsolutions.com/Policy/PolicyListing.aspx?S=36030635)  
* If students wish to **enroll in a Non-District Course** AND plan to add the course credits to their high school transcript, they must **complete the Non-District Course Intent Form**. The form and process is found on the Counseling Department webpage for each high school or on the [DUSD Website](https://www.dublinusd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=443955&type=d&termREC_ID=&pREC_ID=987072).  
* The student needs to order an official transcript from the outside program to be delivered directly to the counseling department at their high school, and the credits will be added a permanent record to the transcript per the board policy.   
* Once an outside course is posted onto the high school transcript, the course, credits, and grades earned will not be removed.    
* Only courses on the official DUSD high school transcript qualify for acceleration or placement decisions.

**Schedule Changes**

**Schedule changes will occur during the first 15 school days of each semester for the following reasons ONLY:**

1. A student is missing a class in their instructional day or missing a course required for graduation  
2. The electronic scheduling system generated an error (ex. duplicate courses)  
3. A student enrolled in an ROP class at another school site has transportation or schedule conflicts  
4. Course Level change:   
   1. **Criteria:** A teacher recommends a course change to a **lower** level from an Honors/AP course based upon academic or mental health concerns and requires a student-teacher conversation.  
   2. **Process:** The teacher must email the student’s counselor with the recommendation for a course level change.  
   3. **Deadline:** As early as possible, but no later than 15 school days after the first day of instruction in the course.   
   4. **Availability:** Changes depend on space. If there is no space available in the recommended course, the schedule change may involve a Teacher Assistant (TA) assignment or an available elective. 

**Course withdrawal after the first fifteen (15) school days of each semester:**

* **All course withdrawals are handled through the student's counselor.**   
  * Students must discuss the course withdrawal with their teacher and assigned counselor.   
  * The teacher will sign the Change of Program form provided by the counselor indicating they have discussed the change of program with the student.   
  * Parent/guardian signatures are obtained and the change of program form is returned to the counselor who then obtains admin signature for final approval.   
* For students who drop after the first fifteen (15) days of school, grades will reflect the following on the high school transcript:


| Withdrawal Timing | Transcript Impact | Grade Policy |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Within First Quarter | "NM" (No Mark) | For students earning 60% or above. |
| Within First Quarter | "F" Grade | For students earning below 60%. |
| After First Quarter | No New Course | Students cannot drop after the first quarter. |

  * Students who drop a course within the first five weeks will start with a fresh grade in the new course. Students who drop a course within weeks 6-9 will carry over the existing grade from the dropped class.  
* Full year courses or semester courses that are graduation requirements can only be dropped if there is space available in the corresponding lower-level course.  
* Full year courses not required for graduation, including Honors and AP courses, can be dropped at the semester with the grade of record being placed on the high school transcript.  
* Students can drop an Honors or AP class based on concerns about academic performance and if there is space available in a lower level course. Dropped Honors/AP classes will follow the same grade policies as described above.

**Schedule changes will not be granted at any time for the following reasons:**

1. Change of teacher  
2. Change of sequence of classes during the day or change of Gael Period  
3. Change of elective classes that are different from the original course selection

|  Repeating Classes |
| :---: |

* We understand there are times our students face challenges and difficult life situations.  If a student earned a D or F in a class required for graduation or admission to the UC/CSU system, DUSD does offer options to remediate the grade and credit. Please discuss options with the student’s counselor.  
* Students must repeat any course(s) required for graduation in which they received a letter grade of  F or no credit (NM).  
* Valley HS (continuation) can remediate classes in which they received an F and can retake classes in which they received an NM.  
* We recommend repeating courses required for college admission in which the student earned a grade lower than a C-.  
* A student will only receive credit for the same class once. If a student repeats a class to improve the letter grade of "D" they will receive credit only once. 

**Credit Recovery and Grade Improvement Options:**

1. DUSD Summer School.  Two sessions of summer offer an opportunity for students to retake some graduation requirements.    
2. Edgenuity: online platform providing an option for retaking graduation requirements.  Students will co-enroll at DUSD’s York Alternative Learning Center (YALC).   
3. Students may retake courses from accredited outside programs with pre-approval from their counselor.  The process for approval is found on the Counseling Department website for each high school. Refer to DUSD [Board Policy 6146.11 and Administrative Regulation 6146.11](https://simbli.eboardsolutions.com/Policy/PolicyListing.aspx?S=36030635)

| DUSD Course Offerings |
| :---: |

**Availability of Courses at a Particular Campus**

All courses listed are offered at both Dublin High School and Emerald High School unless a specific school site is listed under the course number. **Students should check their course selection guide for a complete list of classes available to them in the coming year.** While all courses in this catalog have been approved by the Board of Trustees, the 2025-26 schedule of classes and student placement in any particular class will be contingent on the number of requests for particular courses and scheduling availability. Course requests do not guarantee enrollment.  Please note that many Regional Occupation Program (ROP) courses are offered at sites outside of the Dublin Unified School District. Students are required to arrange their own transportation to ROP classes.

**Course Level Designations**

**Non-College Preparatory Course:** Meets DUSD graduation requirements. Example:  Physical Education

**College Preparatory Class:** Class curriculum has been approved by the University of California (UC) system to qualify for a college preparatory designation and meet the course requirements for college admissions. 

**Advanced Class:** Rigorous version of the college preparatory class with the same name. These courses are not weighted for purposes of calculating a student’s grade point average.

**Honors Class**: Course will offer an increased depth and breadth in the given subject. Honors classes carry a weighted grade for graduation and some colleges and universities.  Honors weighted courses are designated with a (HP) in the course handbook and on the student’s transcript.  For UC/CSU admissions, Honors courses are only weighted if taken in 10th, 11th or 12th grades.

**Advanced Placement (AP) Class**: AP classes are college level classes taught on a high school campus. AP classes are very challenging and include significantly more work than the college prep classes. Other courses, commitments outside of school, time management skills, and academic preparation are all vital factors to consider when deciding to enroll in an AP class. Students are encouraged to limit the number of AP courses they take simultaneously. Students are also encouraged to take the standardized AP exam in the spring, as a passing score on the exam may qualify the student for college credit, depending on the college policy. AP courses are also weighted for purposes of calculating a student’s high school GPA. For UC/CSU admissions, AP courses are only weighted if taken in 10th, 11th or 12th grades.

![][image2]

**Introductory Engineering Courses**

**PLTW Introduction To Engineering Design (IED)**  
Course Number:			717015  
Grade Level:			9-l2  
Length:				1 year  
Essential Skills:			None  
Graduation: 			Elective credit  
College Prep:			UC/CSU ”D” area lab science credit with a grade of “C” or better

In this course, students use 3D solid modeling design software to help them design solutions to solve proposed problems. Students will learn how to document their work and communicate solutions to peers and members of the professional community. The major focus of the IED course is to expose students to the design process, research and analysis, teamwork, communication methods, global and human impacts, engineering standards and technical documentation. This is one of the two recommended first-year courses for students interested in the Engineering & Computer Science Pathway.  
**Work outside of class:** Homework is typically the completion of classwork or projects not completed within the class period that may need to be completed at home.

**PLTW Environmental Sustainability (ES)**   
Course Number: 			717021  
**School Site:			Dublin High School**  
Grade Level: 			9-l2  
Length:				None  
Graduation:                                	Elective credit  
College Prep:			UC/CSU ‘G’ area  elective credit 

Environmental Sustainability (ES) is a high school-level specialization course in PLTW Engineering. In ES, students investigate and design solutions to solve real-world challenges related to clean drinking water, a stable food supply, and renewable energy. Students are introduced to environmental issues and use the engineering design process to research and design potential solutions. Through both individual and collaborative team activities, projects, and problems, students problem solve as they practice common design and scientific protocols such as project management, lab techniques, and peer review. Students develop skills in designing experiments, conducting research, executing technical skills, documenting design solutions according to accepted technical standards, and creating presentations to communicate solutions. Students in ES will be introduced to Raspberry Pi and other microcontroller technology to monitor environmental sensors and perform simple mechanical operations within an environmental context.   
**Work outside of class**: Homework is typically the completion of classwork or projects not completed within the class period that may need to be completed at home.

**Foundational Engineering Courses**

**PLTW Principles of Engineering Honors (POE) (HP)**  
Course Number: 			717010  
Grade Level: 			10-l2  
Length: 				1 year  
Essential Skills: 	Completion of Algebra with a ‘B’ or higher (Concurrent enrollment in Algebra 2 or above highly recommended), Successful completion of CSE, CSP, ES or IED & Engineering Teacher Recommendation, [Completed POE Course Selection Form](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfJ_k7xWoVNO53D8g7l04fNm1eBD5GX3l1qdnG_5yzJASWCWA/viewform)   
Graduation: 			Elective credit  
College Prep:	UC/CSU ‘D’ science credit, grade C or higher grade is weighted. Articulated to LPC ENGIN 10

This survey course of engineering exposes students to many of the major concepts they’ll encounter in a college engineering course of study. These concepts will rely heavily on mathematical and computational skills. Students will also employ engineering, simulation, and scientific concepts in the solution of engineering design problems. Students have an opportunity to investigate engineering and high-tech careers and to develop skills and understanding of engineering concepts. They develop problem-solving skills and apply their knowledge of research and design to create solutions to various challenges. Students also learn how to document their work and communicate their solutions to peers and members of the professional community. This is a recommended course for all students in the Engineering pathway. Students earning a B or better in this course earn 2 units of college credit through Las Positas College.   
**Work outside of class:** Homework is typically assigned weekly with daily check-offs and consists of 2-4 multi-step problems. In addition, classwork or projects not completed within the class period may need to be completed at home.  

**Specialized Engineering Courses**

**ROP PLTW Honors Aerospace Engineering (HP)**  
Course Number:			715242  
**School Site			Foothill High School (Alternating years: 2024-25, 2026-27, 2028-29)**  
Grade Level:			11-l2  
Length:				1 year  
Essential Skills:			Completion of Principles of Engineering  
Graduation: 			Elective credit  
College Prep:			UC/CSU ”D” area lab science credit with a grade of “C” or better

Aerospace Engineering is a high school-level course intended to propel students’ learning in the fundamentals of atmospheric and space flight. As they explore the physics of flight, students bring the concepts to life by designing an airfoil, propulsion system, and rockets. They learn basic orbital mechanics using industry-standard software. They also explore robot systems through projects such as remotely operated vehicles. The course exposes students to some of the major concepts that they will encounter in a post-secondary engineering course of study in the area of aerospace engineering.  
**NOTE**:  Must provide your own transportation.

**ROP Honors Civil Engineering and Architecture (CEA)**  
Course Number:	715241  
**School Site:	Livermore High School**   
Grade Level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year/1 period per day     
Essential Skills:	Completion of POE or IED  
Graduation:	Physical Science credit  
College Credit:	UC/CSU "D" area lab science credit with grade of “C” or better, weighted course 			  
ROP Civil engineering has a significant role in the life of every human being, though one may not truly sense its importance in our daily routines.  Architecture is the art / practice of designing and constructing buildings.  To help students explore these career fields, students learn about various aspects of civil engineering and architecture and apply their knowledge to the design and development of residential and commercial properties and structures. The honors course in American Literature is a chronological and thematic approach to major writers and literary movements from the 17th through the 21st centuries. This course focuses on both fiction and nonfiction while building proficiency in deep analysis of both rhetorical and literary strategies used by writers as we examine the development of the “American Identity.” Students explore a variety of writing genres with emphasis on short and long analytical essays; give succinct, analytical presentations; work on collaborative and individual research projects; and delve deeply into texts through Socratic Seminars. Speaking in small groups and with the entire class is a common occurrence and is mandatory for success. Homework is designed to practice concepts, ideas, and skills from class, to give time for independent reading to prepare for class, and to work on longer-term assignments like essays and presentations. If a student is to be successful in this course, they should have a love of reading and literature. Students should have writing skills and analysis depth on a level at or near that of an AP Literature student, as this is a close stepping stone for success senior year in AP Literature.

Course Number:	753386

Historically, texts read in English classes come from the traditional literary canon, providing students a limited perspective that does not include minoritized groups or authors.  This course is designed to introduce students to literature written by African American authors and the unique perspective they bring to American culture and identity formation.  Texts read in this course will build upon W.E.B. DuBois’ concept of Double Consciousness, first coined in *The Souls of Black Folk*, and will focus on the duality within identity.  Units will focus on African American authors from different time periods beginning with the Harlem Renaissance and ending with modern-day.  Students will be asked to analyze the texts and the author’s commentary on identity through class discussions and various writing assignments, with a culminating identity project focusing on Double Consciousness within the student’s own identity.  
**Work outside of class:** 30 minutes per day, 5 days per week, plus additional time for test preparation.

**Deconstructing Race**  
Course Number:		753388  
Grade: 		                        	12  
Length:			          	1 semester	  
Essential Skills:		Completion of  English 3   
Graduation:		English credits  
College Prep:		          	UC/CSU “B” area \- English credit with a grade of “C” or better  
Racism has been historically used as a tool to separate people in order to justify colonialism, enslavement, oppression, and prejudice. In this course students will trace the historical development of structural racism in American society; race is not biological but is a social construct that categorizes people through their supposed physical and cognitive differences. The course will survey the social relationships of African Americans, Latinx, Asian Americans, Arab Americans, and Indigenous peoples. We will trace race and ethnicity as dynamic, complex ideological and cultural forces that shape all social institutions, interpersonal relationships, and internal experiences. The course covers grade-level reading, writing, language, and speaking and listening standards in the Common Core. Texts for the course will be varied and multi-modal; students will learn to navigate through and think critically about  print (novels, essays), podcasts, social media platforms, videos, and peer-reviewed journals.  
**Work outside of class:** 30 minutes per day, 5 days per week, plus additional time for test preparation.

This course is dedicated to the dystopian genre. AP Human Geography introduces high school students to college-level introductory human geography or cultural geography. The content is presented thematically rather than regionally and is organized around the discipline’s main subfields: economic geography, cultural geography, political geography, and urban geography. The approach is spatial and problem oriented. Case studies are drawn from all world regions, with an emphasis on understanding the world in which we live today. Historical information serves to enrich analysis of the impacts of phenomena such as globalization, colonialism, and human–environment relationships on places, regions, cultural landscapes, and patterns of interaction. The goal for the course is for students to become more geoliterate, more engaged in contemporary global issues, and more informed about multicultural viewpoints. They will develop skills in approaching problems geographically, using maps and geospatial technologies, thinking critically about texts and graphic images, interpreting cultural landscapes, and applying geographic concepts such as scale, region, diffusion, interdependence, and spatial interaction, among others. Students will see geography as a discipline relevant to the world in which they live; as a source of ideas for identifying, clarifying, and solving problems at various scales; and as a key component of building global citizenship and environmental stewardship.   
**Work outside of class:** 60 minutes a day

**Math Acceleration**  
Enrollment in the next level of mathematics requires successful completion of the current math course.  There is no Credit by Exam to move to the next level of mathematics. Courses must be taken sequentially, unless otherwise noted. Students who have the desire to to accelerate their mathematics course of study after completing 8th grade have the ability to do so in one of two ways:

1) Dual Enrollment  
   Students may accelerate their math pathway by taking two math courses simultaneously.  Dual Enrollment options are: Algebra I and Geometry, Geometry and Advanced Algebra II, AP Statistics and PreCalculus, or AP Statistics and AP Calculus AB or BC

2) Alternative Credit Programs  
   Refer to DUSD [Board Policy 6146.11 and Administrative Regulation 6146.11](https://simbli.eboardsolutions.com/Policy/PolicyListing.aspx?S=36030635)  
   Students may take up to 20 credits of mathematics (and no more than 40 credits in all subject areas combined) outside of DUSD to fulfill the DUSD graduation requirements. We do not recommend that students use an alternative credit program to fulfill the requirements for Algebra I or Algebra II, as these are foundational courses critical to the success of higher-level courses. High school math teachers have found that students taking courses through the alternative credit program have the most success if they enroll in a Geometry summer course. Students must **complete the Non-District Course Intent Form**. Please speak with a counselor or visit the Counseling Department webpage for each high school or on the [DUSD Website](https://www.dublinusd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=443955&type=d&termREC_ID=&pREC_ID=987072) for more information regarding alternative credit programs.

This course is a year long **intermediate** level dance course **which builds on the fundamentals of dance taught in Dance 1\.** The purpose of this class is to increase one’s body awareness and technique while demonstrating dance movement.  Through the continued exploration of a variety of dance genres, including jazz, creative (modern) movement, ballet, and cultural dance (hip hop and more), students will advance their dance vocabulary, deepen their connection between the physical and emotional components of dance and continue to broaden their choreography and technical skills.  Students will continue to explore the elements of self-expression through improvisational work and self-choreographed pieces.  The students will prepare for performance opportunities through rehearsal of routines, staging awareness, and technical preparation for live audiences in costumed performances. Students will perform in the semester dance concerts or will be expected to complete an alternate assessment.

The class is for students who wish to excel in the art of dance through the experience of exposure to advanced techniques. This is a beginner level course in the fundamentals of acting. You will establish an understanding of all aspects of the theater making process including: content vocabulary, acquiring basic skills in an actor’s process, and all of the production jobs in theater. Through exercises, analysis and improvisations, the student actor will explore their mind, body, and voice as the actor’s primary creative resources when creating a character. Units will include Improvisation, Use of Voice, Pantomime, Scene Study, and Character Analysis. In theater, as in life, we learn by doing. This is an intermediate level Theater Class. Within each unit of study there will be elements of theater making partnered with textual analysis. While you study each era you will also be collaborating in a group on an original piece of theater that reflects the themes and characteristics of the time period. Along with performance based assessments you will also have some traditional assessments in the form of quizzes and tests. Please be prepared that this is a practical class and you should expect to be actively participating as an essential component of this class.

This is an advanced level acting class; it is modeled after college level courses. In this class you will begin to deepen your connection to characters and your performance skills by exploring the work of influential directors such as Konstantin Stanislavsky, Sanford Meisner, Lee Strasberg (Method Acting), Stella Adler and Anne Bogart to name a few. We will also work on defining what it means to be “in the moment” and what makes a believable and truthful performance through your rehearsal of Monologues, two person scenes, improvisations and group scenes. In Theatre, you are the art that is being viewed. Please be prepared that this is a practical class and you should expect to be actively participating as an essential component of this class.   
\*\*\*Important Note 1: Students are welcome to take this class more than once.  
\*\*\*Important Note 2: Students who enroll in this class will be required to participate in 1-2 showcase performances each year. **Work outside of class:** 30 minutes a day, 5 times a week, plus additional time for performance preparation (details will be provided via syllabus on the first day of class)

The course and textbook are based on the California SBE-adopted Next Generation Science Standards (NGSS) for Public Schools within the scope of the life sciences. In this course, the NGSS framework will support students’ learning within 5 broad topics 1\) Structure and Function, 2\) Inheritance and Variation of Traits, 3\) Matter and Energy in Organisms and Ecosystems, 4\) Interdependent Relationships in Ecosystems, and 5\) Natural Selection and Evolution. **Biotechnology**  
Course Number:	713731  
**School Site: 	Dublin High School**  
Grade level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Biology and Chemistry  
Graduation:	Science elective  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC”D” lab science requirement with a grade of “C” or better

Biotechnology is a lab-intensive course designed to combine molecular biology with practical applications. Currently, credit is offered from Ohlone College upon successful mastery of biotechnology skills and content  (earning a B or better). Because this is a college course, students are expected to treat it as such, including time commitments involved. Students should already have a mastery of solution-making calculations and significant figures from their previous chemistry course. Chemistry is heavily emphasized. The main goals of the course are gaining a deeper understanding of: molecular genetics, proteins, lab protocols and techniques, and an introduction to Biotechnology in the world today. Students will be exposed to DNA fingerprinting, gene mapping, electrophoresis and PCR, as well as activities that relate biotechnology to daily life. Students will also have the opportunity to experience the basics of microbiology, human genetics, and exploration of bioethical issues. This course will prepare students for future science coursework in college as well as introduce the area of Biotechnology as a possible future career. At the conclusion of the course, students will receive college credit and/or proceed to the next course in the biotechnology major.  
**Work outside of class**: 3-5 hours a week for the purpose of preview, review, and extension. Further time may be spent perfecting solution concentration calculations as homework, as well as lab techniques and understanding the various functions of a biotechnology laboratory. After school hours may be required to master certain lab practical skills and concepts.

Description:  This semester-long course will provide students with a deep exploration of the field of zoology, focusing on animal biology, diversity, behavior, evolution, and ecology. Aligned with the Next Generation Science Standards (NGSS), this course will offer an integrative approach to understanding animals and their roles in ecosystems. **AP Biology (HP)**  
Course Number:	713757  
Grade Level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Biology and Chemistry  
Graduation:	Fulfills life science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D”  requirement with a grade of “C” or better; colleges may   
	award credit upon passing the national AP Exam in May. Weighted course.

AP Biology is a rigorous college-level course, requiring self-motivated and independent learners. This course extends and deepens those concepts developed in the first year Biology course, preparing the student to take the AP Biology Exam in May. The content is predicated around the Four Big Ideas of AP Biology as defined by College Board including Evolution, Energy and Homeostasis, Information Transfer, and System Interactions. Critical thinking, lab work, and scientific writing are emphasized. There are weekly quizzes, frequent multi-day labs, and unit tests monthly. Unit tests are modeled after the AP exam, and require application of concepts and strong scientific reasoning, rather than memorization of content. Significant time outside of class is required for assignments, project work, test corrections, and test preparation. To ensure that the class may complete all units of study prior to mid-April, there is a significant summer homework assignment due weekly during June, July, and August. Due to the rigorous nature of the course, only students with a true interest in the subject of Biology should undertake this class. All students are expected to prepare for and take the Advanced Placement Biology Exam.     
**Work outside of class**: 5-8 hours a week, preview and practice to support conceptual knowledge, critical thinking, and communicating scientific topics in writing. “Extension” assignments may be required to analyze and communicate laboratory exercises, and to review problems to strengthen biology topics covered in previous courses.  
**Summer Work:  There are a significant number of homework assignments due weekly in both June and July.** 

**AP Environmental Science**  
Course Number:	713788  
Grade Level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year   
Essential Skills:	Concurrent enrollment in or successful completion of Algebra II, plus successful completion of at least one other Laboratory science course.  
Graduation:	Physical Science and Life Science elective  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D”requirement with a grade of “C” or better; colleges may award credit upon passing the national exam in May; this is a weighted course.

Students gain the knowledge and skills to understand cause and management of environmental issues and interactions. Learn basic laboratory and field techniques including specimen sampling and processing, site monitoring, documentation, inspection and emergency response. Become familiar with the Geographic Information Systems (GIS). Incorporate academic rigor with practical application by exploring the links between environment, politics, and economics. Gain a broad awareness of environmental science and technological career opportunities through involvement with local environmental businesses, educational research institutes, and national labs. Students should be prepared to participate in outdoor field work requiring some physical activity and willingness to get dirty. In addition to the core requirements outlined above, study and expectations are designed to provide students with an academic experience parallel to that of the college level, while promoting critical thinking skills involved in independent research studies. A significant amount of reading and research is required. All students are expected to prepare for and take the Advanced Placement Environmental Science Exam.   
**Work outside of class**: 45-60 minutes a day or 4-6 hours a week, preview and practice to support conceptual knowledge, qualitative and quantitative problems solving, and communicating scientific environmental topics orally and in writing.

**Chemistry**  
Course Number:	713766  
Grade Level:	10-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Biology, successful completion of Algebra 1 with “C” or better and concurrent enrollment in Geometry. Current enrollment in Algebra II or higher is recommended.  
Graduation:	Fulfills physical science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC physical lab science”D” requirement with a grade of “C” or better

Chemistry deals with the nature of materials in our world and how they change and combine to form new substances. This course is for students intending on attending a 4-year college or university. Topics include: the atomic model of matter; bulk properties of materials, bonding and molecular structure, chemical reactions; chemical equilibrium. Students should expect to spend time outside of class, in practice problem sets, reading and the preparation of lab reports. The course material supports the physical science and earth science core standards of the Next Generation Science Standards (NGSS). Use of a scientific calculator in class and outside of the class is required for this course. Chemistry students typically spend approximately 30-45 minutes 3 times per week on homework assignments. Most (\~80%) of the homework is practice of chemistry concepts and quantitative problem solving skills.   
**Work outside of class**: 30-45 minutes a day, 3 times a week.  Possible additional review work necessary for exams and semester finals.

**Honors Chemistry (HP)**  
Course Number:	713767  
Grade Level:	10-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Students who are successful in Honors Chemistry generally come into the course with strong competency in previous sciences and math courses. Students must have concurrent enrollment in Alg II or higher and score a successful grade on the Chemistry Readiness Test.  **Discuss placement with current science teacher.**  
Graduation:	Fulfills physical science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D”  requirement with a grade of “C” or better, weighted course (weighted in grade 10 and above on the college prep GPA, weighted in cumulative GPA if taken in grade 9 or summer after grade 9.)

Honors Chemistry is a rigorous college prep class meant for students who have demonstrated success in mathematics and previous STEM courses, and who intend to go onto higher level science courses such as AP Chemistry, AP Biology, Honors Anatomy, Honors Physics/AP Physics, or AP Environmental. This class requires that students be self-motivated, detailed and will work both independently and collaboratively on specific assignments.  In order for students to be successful in Honors Chemistry, students must complete non-graded practices and homework routinely and in a timely manner. Detailed formal laboratory notebooks are required and are graded for both detail and accuracy.  Honors chemistry is concerned with the chemical properties of substances. Topics include: properties of matter; atomic theory, electron clouds and probability, periodic trends, chemical formulas, chemical reactions, chemical bonding kinetic theory, the gas laws, properties of solutions, reaction rates, acids and bases, oxidation-reduction and entropy. In addition, the course material supports the physical science and earth science core standards of the Next Generation Science Standards (NGSS).   
**Work outside of class:** 4-5 hours a week; consisting of completing labs, working through practices and checking work online.  Formal laboratory notebooks and typed abstracts are required along with comprehensive project-based first and third quarter assessments

**Earth and Space Science (NGSS)**  
Course Number:	713742  
Grade Level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful Completion of Biology  
Graduation:	Fulfills physical science requirement

Note: due to the labs and activities in this course, excellent attendance is expected.  Earth Science is an elective course intended for students with an interest in astronomy, geology, meteorology, and/or oceanography. The 1st semester is an introduction to astronomy consisting of the characteristics and life cycle of the Sun and stars, the origin and structure of our solar system, asteroid impacts, extrasolar planets, the earth-moon system, and the origin and structure of the universe, The 2st semester covers California hazards: earthquakes, volcanoes, landslides, tsunamis, tornadoes, thunderstorms, lightning, and floods. Students investigate the processes that concentrate energy, the ways in which energy is released, and the accompanying hazards. Coursework involves hands-on activities, computer simulations, creating and interpreting graphs, and projects.   
**Work outside of class**: 20 minutes a day, 3 days a week; consisting of reading assignments, conclusion of  
activities and additional practice or review of concepts.

Forensic Science is a lab based investigative course that teaches students the how and why of evidence collection. Forensic science is important in many careers from the legal system to the medical field. This course prepares students for both the Biomedical Pathway and the ROP Criminal Justice course. Graduation:		Fulfills physical science requirement.  
College Prep:		Fulfills CSU/UC physical lab science “D” requirement with a grade of “C” or better

Physics in the Universe is a one-year interactive and dynamic science course designed to help students understand the scientific principles behind phenomena in their everyday lives. We will use topics such as vehicular motion, electric power production and use, communication technologies, space exploration, and natural disasters to cover physics material including forces, motion, momentum, energy, electromagnetism, waves, & gravity. Students are expected to actively participate in class discussions, lab explorations, group projects, and other activities to develop and demonstrate their mastery of the NGSS standards. Inherent curiosity, willingness to try, and a basic understanding of 1st-year Algebra is needed to successfully participate in this course.   
**Work outside of class:** 20-40 minutes a day, 2-3 hrs a week; may include lecture videos, practice assessments, labs, and projects. Additional time may need to be spent studying.

**Honors Physics**  
Course Number:		713776  
Grade Level: 			11-l2  
Length: 				1 year  
Essential Skills: 			Concurrent enrollment in Precalculus or above; successful completion of all semesters of   
previous math (including Advanced Algebra II or Trigonometry) and science classes   
(including Chemistry)   
Graduation: 			Fulfills physical science requirement  
College Prep: 			Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D”  requirement with a grade of “C” or better, weighted course   
(weighted in grade 10 and above on the college prep GPA, weighted in cumulative GPA if taken in grade 9 or summer after grade 9.)

Honors Physics is concerned with describing the relationship between matter and energy. Topics include: motion and the relationship between force and motion, conservation of energy and momentum, heat and thermodynamics, wave behavior (light, sound, etc.), electric and magnetic phenomena, astronomy and some “modern” physics. The course is aligned with Next Generation Science Standards. Critical thinking and lab work and reporting are emphasized. Trigonometry is an integral part of this course. The second semester final exam is comprehensive and covers topics from the full Honors Physics course. This course is recommended for students intending to pursue a college major in a STEM field, particularly the physical sciences and/or engineering. **\*\*AP Physics C Mechanics may NOT be taken for duplicate credit after Trigonometry-based college-preparatory Honors Physics.**   
**Work outside of class:** 30 minutes a day, for practice and review \- exploring & reinforcing concepts, problem-solving, test prep

**AP Chemistry**   
Course Number:	713764  
Grade Level:	10-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Chemistry and Algebra II. Successful completion of Honors Chemistry is strongly advised  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D” requirement with a grade of “C” or better; colleges may award credit upon passing the national exam in May; this is a weighted course.

AP Chemistry is a rigorous lab-based college-level course, requiring self-motivated and independent learners. This course will extend and deepen concepts acquired in the first year Chemistry course, preparing the student to take the AP Chemistry Exam in May. The content supports the Six Big Ideas of AP Chemistry as defined by the College Board including the structure of matter, properties of matter, chemical reactions, kinetics, chemical thermodynamics, and equilibrium. Critical thinking and lab work and reporting are emphasized. Significant time outside of class is necessary for tests, lab activities, and preparation for the AP Chemistry exam. There are 16 required in-depth guided inquiry labs, and a unit test approximately every 2 weeks.  Students will write high-quality lab reports in a lab notebook. Tests are based on questions similar to those found on the actual AP Chemistry exam. To ensure that students join the class with recent practice in chemistry skills, and so that the class may complete all units of study prior to mid-April, there is a significant summer homework assignment due weekly during June and July. Following the AP Chemistry exam offered in May, the teacher may conduct a survey of common chemistry topics not normally included in the College Board AP Chemistry Course description ( example:  nuclear chemistry, organic chemistry, biochemistry, qualitative analysis).  Due to the nature of the course, only students with a very strong interest in Chemistry should take the class.   
**Work outside of class:** 60 minutes a day, 5 nights a week; practice and preview to support conceptual knowledge, quantitative problems solving, and communicating scientific topics orally and in writing. “Extension” assignments may be required to analyze and communicate laboratory exercises, and to review problems to strengthen chemistry topics covered in previous courses, and/or preview of subsequent lab sessions.  
**Summer Work:  There are a significant number of homework assignments due weekly in both June and July.**  

**AP Physics C Mechanics (Calculus-based Physics)**  
Course Number:	713771  
Grade Level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Concurrent enrollment in AP Calculus or above; successful completion of all semesters of previous math (including Precalcalculus) and science classes (including Chemistry); discuss placement with the instructor  
Graduation:	Fulfills physical science requirement.  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC lab science “D” requirement with a grade of “C” or better; colleges may award credit upon passing the national exam in May; this is a weighted course.

This course is a rigorous college-level course, requiring self-motivated and independent learners; it is designed for students planning to specialize in a science or engineering major. The course focuses on topics of Mechanics, such as: kinematics; Newton’s laws of motion; work, energy and power; systems of particles and linear momentum; circular motion and rotation; oscillations; and gravitation. (After the AP test, students may also explore other topics such as heat and thermodynamics, wave behavior (light, sound, etc.), electric and magnetic phenomena, astronomy and some “modern” physics.  AP Physics C Mechanics students must: (a) develop a deep understanding of foundational principles of physics in classical mechanics by applying these principles to complex physical situations that combine multiple aspects of physics rather than present concepts in isolation; (b) design and conduct inquiry-based laboratory investigations to solve problems through first-hand observations, data collection, analysis and interpretation, and document these experiences; (c) develop critical thinking skills through applying methods of differential and integral **Calculus** to formulate physical principles and solve complex physical problems. There is extensive summer homework due each week during the summer, with the first unit exam the first week of school. Due to potential for course impaction, please choose alternate science courses, such as Advanced Physics. **\*\*This course may NOT be taken for duplicate credit after Trigonometry-based college-preparatory Honors Physics.**   
**Work outside of class:**  60 minutes a day, often more (intense, college-level problem-solving)

**Biomedical Sciences Pathway Classes** 

**Principles of Biomedical Science (PLTW)**  
Course Number:	713733  
Grade level:	9-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Concurrent enrollment or completion of Biology and Biomedical Pathway application completed  
Graduation:	Fulfills the 3rd year elective science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC “D” lab science requirement with a grade of “C” or better

In this course, students explore concepts of biology and medicine as they take on roles of different medical professionals to solve real-world problems. Over the course of the year, students are challenged in various scenarios including investigating a crime scene to solve a mystery, diagnosing and proposing treatment to patients in a family medical practice, to tracking down and containing a medical outbreak at a local hospital, stabilizing a patient during an emergency, and collaborating with others to design solutions to local and global medical problems. The activities and projects introduce students to human physiology, medicine, and research processes. This course provides an overview of all the courses in the Biomedical Sciences program and lays the scientific foundation for subsequent courses. There is a cumulative final exam at the end that will test knowledge from both semesters.  
**Work outside of class:** 30 \- 60 minutes a day, review and extension, especially Internet research and analysis of concepts learned. A detailed lab notebook will be kept.

**Human Body Systems (PLTW)**  
Course Number:	713785  
Grade level:	10-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Biology and  Biomedical Pathway application completed  
Graduation:	Fulfills life science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC “D” lab science requirement with a grade of “C” or better  
	 	  
Students will examine the interactions of human body systems as they explore identity, power, movement, protection, and homoeostasis. Students will design experiments, investigate the structures and functions of the human body, and use data acquisition software to monitor body functions such as muscle movement, reflexes, voluntary action and respiration. Exploring science in action, students build organs and tissues on a mannequin, work through interesting real world cases and often play the roles of biomedical professionals to solve medical mysteries. There is a cumulative final exam at the end that will test knowledge from both semesters.  
**Work outside of class:** 1-2 hours a week; review and extension, especially Internet research and analysis of concepts learned. A detailed lab notebook will be kept.

**Honors Biomedical Innovation (HP)  (PLTW)**  
Course Number:	713737  
Grade level:	12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of Biology and Chemistry (successful completion of an Honors or AP level science class recommended)   
Graduation:                                   Fulfills 10 credits of elective credit  
College Prep:                                UC/CSU “D” area elective course, weighted if student earns a “C” or better

Biomedical Innovation (PLTW) is a UC “G” elective Honors course.  Senior students apply their knowledge and skills to answer questions and solve problems related to biomedical sciences. Problems include: designing an effective emergency room, exploring human physiology through direct testing, designing a medical innovation, investigating environmental health, combating a public health issue and an independent project of their choice.  Much of this work requires a strong background in Biology, Chemistry and Medicine.  Students must have a good work ethic and be able to work independently to meet deadlines and prepare presentations.  There is a cumulative final exam at the end of the second semester that tests knowledge from both semesters. Priority enrollment is given to seniors in the PLTW Biomedical Pathway, as this serves as the Capstone course for the program.  
**Work outside of class:** 60 minutes a day

**Honors Medical Interventions (HP) (PLTW)**  
Course Number:	713736  
Grade level:	11-12  
Length:	1 year  
Essential Skills:	Successful completion of an Honors or AP level science course,  participation in PLTW Biomedical Pathway   
Graduation:	Fulfills life science requirement  
College Prep:	Fulfills CSU/UC “d” lab science requirement with a grade of “C” or better, weighted grade

Students follow the life of a fictitious family as they investigate how to prevent, diagnose, and treat disease. They will learn about various biomedical careers through case studies, and will even be asked to research and play the role of these biomedical professionals in many instances. They will also interact with actual biomedical professionals in our community through guest speaker visits and unit projects. The four main units are Infectious Disease, Genetic Screening, Cancer, and Organ Failure. Within these, students will explore how to detect and fight infection, screen and evaluate the code in human DNA, evaluate cancer treatment options, and prevail when the organs of the body begin to fail. Lifestyle choices and preventive measures are emphasized throughout the course as well as the important role that scientific thinking and engineering design play in the development of interventions of the future. Students will also be required to conduct their own independent “Connect to the Community” project in which they will design a community service project aimed at bettering the health of people on campus or in their local community. There is a cumulative final exam at the end that will test knowledge from both semesters.  
**Work outside of class:** 30-60 minutes a day; preview, review, and extension, especially Internet research, lab report writing, and analysis of concepts learned. Further time outside of class may be required for the unit projects and independent community service projects. Many multi-day complex biotechnology labs will be performed and a detailed lab notebook will be kept with several formal lab reports.

The purpose of the high school Special Education program is to meet the individual needs of students with an Individual Education Plan (IEP) in the least restrictive environment.  In addition to the full array of courses available to all DUSD high school students, a variety of specialized academic instruction classes are offered based on the student's IEP. Additionally, related services, such as speech and language, psychological services, and occupational therapy, are provided as designated in the student's IEP. Special education classes are not college preparatory (i.e., do not meet A-G requirements), and enrollment is restricted to students who have these classes included as part of their IEP.

[**TVROP 2026-2027  Course Catalog**](https://www.tvrop.org/our-classes/course-catalog)

**General Information**  
Tri-Valley Regional Occupational Program (ROP) offers college level classes to students that develop skills necessary for post secondary education or training following completion of high school or the ROP class, that sequence directly into business, industry and/or continuing education.  Classes are offered at Amador, Dublin, Foothill, Granada, and Livermore, High Schools and Las Positas College. ROP classes are college and career preparation classes which are credited in the same manner as other elective classes. Excellent attendance is required for all ROP classes.

**Types of ROP Classes**

* **Classroom/Laboratory:** Learning environments for ROP classes include worksites, drafting lab, auto shop and graphics lab.  
* **Community Classroom:** Combines classroom education and non-paid work-based training assignments.  After six to nine weeks of classroom  instruction, students are placed at a community business/work-site.  Once a student is placed, he/she spends a minimum of two hours per day, two to four days per week, at their  assignment.  
* **Cooperative Vocational Education (CVE):** Involves classroom learning and paid work-based training.  The work-site training is similar to the Community Classroom program.  However, in the CVE program the student earns wages and additional credits.

**Community College Credit By Exam**  
This enables high school students to earn college credit.  ROP classes, equivalent to introductory classes in approved community college programs in the same occupational area, may be granted college credit.  Students who have completed the ROP articulation process for their class with a "B" or better do not need to repeat the class at the community college.  Programs are articulated with community colleges to encourage students to continue advanced training in a 2-year certificate program. 

All community college articulations refer to Las Positas and/or Chabot Colleges unless otherwise noted.  See your counselor for clarification.  These credits transfer to most 4 year universities at no cost to you.   

**Registration/Eligibility**  
While seniors have priority, juniors and sophomores are eligible to enroll in ROP classes, as well.  High school students may enroll in classes with the College and Career Specialist or the counselor/scheduling administrator at the high school.  ROP classes comply with all mandates of Public Law 101476\.  Specific times of classes are determined as individual schools develop their master schedules and students are placed accordingly.

**Repeat Policy**  
Credit is awarded for ROP classes in the same manner as all high school credit  ROP classes may not be repeated for credit.  Non-credit repetition will be allowed for enrichment or to raise a letter grade.  Some ROP subjects offer first and second year opportunities.  ROP courses designated as I & II year programs allow students to receive credit in both years.

**High School Credit**  
Credit for ROP courses is determined by the number of hours in which the student is enrolled:    
***Three hour program \= 30 credits per year;  Two hour program \= 20 credits per year;  One hour program \= 10 credits per year***  
Some ROP classes have been approved for High School graduation subject requirements.  These classes are noted as **“Alternate Graduation Credit”**.

**Travel Time**  
Students traveling between schools are allowed adequate time to report to classes on a timely basis.

**Transportation**  
Public bus transportation (Wheels) tickets are available through the Career Center for students participating in ROP classes at sites other than their home school.
